---
import { withBase } from '../../lib/url';
import Prose from '../../layouts/Prose.astro';
import PlacementLookup from '../../components/course/PlacementLookup.astro';
import { TOOLS } from '../../lib/tools';

const tool = TOOLS.find((t) => t.slug === 'placement-lookup')!;
---

<Prose
  title={tool.title}
  description={tool.description}
  crumbs={[{ name: 'Tools', href: '/tools/' }, { name: tool.title }]}
  kicker="Practice Tools"
>
  <p>
    The heart of the Renaissance casebooks is the placement series: for every house, a reading
    of every figure that may stand in it. This tool is a concordance of that series: pick a
    figure and a house and read what the sources say of exactly that placement, in short cited
    excerpts, with a link to the full combination page where one exists. It indexes Cattan's
    Book II (the richest of the series) alongside the pseudo-Agrippa, Heydon and Crowley.
  </p>
  <p>
    A concordance, not an oracle: <a href={withBase('/course/the-twelve-houses/')}>Lesson 5</a> introduces
    the lookup, and Lesson 11 uses it in finished readings. A placement entry is a finding, to
    be selected by the question's register and weighed inside a method, never a pre-written
    answer to be read off. The same material
    can be browsed whole from <a href={withBase('/figures/')}>the figures</a> and
    <a href={withBase('/houses/')}>the houses</a>.
  </p>

  <PlacementLookup />
</Prose>
